data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, the compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` when called on an array. Since **expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls**, this fails at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches prevent the compiler from selecting the span overload, keeping the call within what expression trees can represent. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` instead of `arr.Reverse()`.
